@startuml Parallel Fan-Out - Structured Concurrency with Fail-Fast

title Parallel Fan-Out: StructuredTaskScope with Virtual Threads

participant Main as main
participant "StructuredTaskScope" as scope
participant "Virtual Thread A" as taskA
participant "Virtual Thread B" as taskB
participant "Virtual Thread C" as taskC
participant "Result Aggregator" as aggregator

== Setup ==

main -> scope: Parallel.run(List.of(taskA, taskB, taskC))
note right of scope
  StructuredTaskScope Java 21+ preview
  Guaranteed cleanup (try-with-resources pattern)
  Virtual threads for lightweight concurrency
end note

== Fan-Out: Spawn All Tasks ==

scope -> taskA: fork()
scope -> taskB: fork()
scope -> taskC: fork()

note right of scope
  All 3 tasks running concurrently
  Each in its own virtual thread
  No OS thread overhead
end note

== Parallel Processing ==

par Concurrent Execution
  taskA -> taskA: compute partition 1
  taskA -> taskA: ~1000ms
  taskB -> taskB: compute partition 2
  taskB -> taskB: ~500ms
  taskC -> taskC: compute partition 3
  taskC -> taskC: ~2000ms
end

== Early Failure: Fail-Fast ==

taskB -> taskB: data validation fails
taskB -> taskB: throw IllegalArgumentException
taskB -> scope: exception in task

note right of scope
  IMMEDIATE reaction to failure:
  1. Cancel other tasks
  2. Cleanup resources
  3. Return exception to caller
end note

scope -> taskA: cancel() [via Thread.interrupt()]
taskA -> taskA: receives interrupt
taskA -> taskA: InterruptedException
taskA -> taskA: cleanup + exit

scope -> taskC: cancel() [via Thread.interrupt()]
taskC -> taskC: receives interrupt
taskC -> taskC: InterruptedException
taskC -> taskC: cleanup + exit

note right of scope
  taskA had ~500ms left to run
  taskC had ~1000ms left to run
  Both cancelled immediately
  No wasted computation
end note

== Resource Cleanup ==

scope -> scope: close() [try-with-resources]
note right of scope
  Guaranteed cleanup:
  - All threads joined
  - Virtual thread resources freed
  - No leaks possible
  (differs from unstructured Thread.start())
end note

== Return to Caller ==

scope --> main: throw exceptions
aggregator -> main: all failures collected
note right of main
  Can choose strategy:
  1. Return first exception (fail-fast default)
  2. Collect all exceptions (fail-all)
  3. Return partial results + exceptions

  Caller must handle:
  ExceptionGroup: multiple exceptions
  or individual exception wrapper
end note

main -> main: handle failure
alt Retry
  main -> scope: retry with different params
else Fallback
  main -> main: use cached/default result
else Propagate
  main -> main: throw to caller
end

== Contrast: Unstructured Concurrency ==

note over main, taskC
  WITHOUT StructuredTaskScope:
  - main calls executor.submit() on each task
  - Tasks run in shared thread pool
  - Failure in B: must manually cancel A, C
  - Can forget cleanup (resource leak)
  - Cascading failures possible
  - Hard to reason about lifetime

  WITH StructuredTaskScope:
  - Scope defines lifetime boundaries
  - Automatic cancellation on failure
  - Guaranteed cleanup (Java guarantees)
  - Virtual threads no thread pool overhead
  - Easy to reason about: scope ← tasks
end note

== Use Cases ==

note right of scope
  Ideal for:
  1. MapReduce patterns
  2. Fan-out/fan-in queries
  3. Batch processing
  4. Parallel array processing
  5. Divide-and-conquer algorithms

  Key advantage:
  - Lightweight: millions of virtual threads
  - Safe: guaranteed cleanup
  - Fast: fail-fast cancellation
  - Clear: structured scope = clear lifetime
end note
